  "real_world_anchor": {
    "primary": "Dragging a heavy suitcase up a ramp at Mumbai Central station — rope pulls at an angle, but only the horizontal part actually moves it forward.",
    "secondary": "A kite string in the wind — the tension in the string has a horizontal pull and a vertical lift, and both matter.",
    "tertiary": "A farmer's bullock ploughing a field — the yoke applies force at an angle; only the horizontal component does useful work."
  },
  "locked_facts": [
    "A vector at angle alpha from the x-axis has component F*cos(alpha) along x and F*sin(alpha) along y.",
    "Components are always perpendicular to each other.",
    "The magnitude of the vector equals the square root of (Fx^2 + Fy^2) — Pythagoras.",
    "Cosine pairs with the axis you measured the angle FROM.",
    "Choosing axes aligned with motion simplifies the equations — never a wrong choice, just a smart one."
  ],
