      "STATE_4": {
        "title": "The Formula — F cosα and F sinα",
        "duration": 12,
        "advance_mode": "auto_after_tts",
        "focal_primitive_id": "formula_box_main",
        "scene_composition": [
          {
            "type": "surface",
            "id": "ground",
            "orientation": "horizontal",
            "position": {
              "x": 120,
              "y": 380
            },
            "length": 420,
            "texture": "rough"
          },
          {
            "type": "body",
            "id": "origin_point",
            "shape": "circle",
            "size": 10,
            "position": {
              "x": 250,
              "y": 372
            },
            "fill_color": "#1F2937",
            "border_color": "#F59E0B",
            "border_width": 2
          },
          {
            "type": "force_arrow",
            "id": "F_arrow",
            "force_id": "main_vector",
            "origin_body_id": "origin_point",
            "origin_anchor": "body_center",
            "color": "#3B82F6",
            "scale_pixels_per_unit": 8
          },
          {
            "type": "force_components",
            "id": "F_components",
            "force_id": "main_vector",
            "decompose_axis": "world_xy",
            "origin_body_id": "origin_point",
            "origin_anchor": "body_center",
            "color": "#F59E0B",
            "scale_pixels_per_unit": 8,
            "animate_in_ms": 200,
            "label_x": "F cosα = {horiz} N",
            "label_y": "F sinα = {vert} N"
          },
          {
            "type": "angle_arc",
            "id": "alpha_arc",
            "center": {
              "x": 250,
              "y": 372
            },
            "radius": 45,
            "from_deg": 0,
            "to_deg": 50,
            "color": "#F59E0B",
            "label": "α = {alpha}°"
          },
          {
            "type": "formula_box",
            "id": "formula_box_main",
            "formula": "Fx = F·cosα\nFy = F·sinα",
            "position": {
              "x": 490,
              "y": 110
            },
            "border_color": "#3B82F6"
          },
          {
            "type": "annotation",
            "id": "memory_rule",
            "text": "MEMORY RULE:\ncos stays WITH the axis\nyou measured α FROM.\nsin goes with the perpendicular.",
            "position": {
              "x": 490,
              "y": 230
            },
            "style": "callout",
            "color": "#10B981"
          },
          {
            "type": "annotation",
            "id": "numeric_check",
            "text": "CHECK: F=10 N, α=50°\n10 × cos(50°) = 6.43 N\n10 × sin(50°) = 7.66 N\n√(6.43² + 7.66²) = 10 ✓",
            "position": {
              "x": 490,
              "y": 370
            },
            "style": "callout",
            "color": "#F59E0B"
          }
        ],
        "teacher_script": {
          "tts_sentences": [
            {
              "id": "s1",
              "text_en": "Now the formulas. In any right triangle, cosine of the angle equals ADJACENT over hypotenuse."
            },
            {
              "id": "s2",
              "text_en": "So the adjacent side equals hypotenuse times cosine. That gives us Fx equals F times cosine alpha."
            },
            {
              "id": "s3",
              "text_en": "Similarly, sine equals opposite over hypotenuse. So Fy equals F times sine alpha."
            },
            {
              "id": "s4",
              "text_en": "Memorize this rule and you will never mix them up: cosine goes with the axis you measured the angle FROM."
            },
            {
              "id": "s5",
              "text_en": "Let us verify. Ten Newtons at fifty degrees: cosine fifty is zero point six four, so Fx is six point four three Newtons. Sine fifty is zero point seven seven, so Fy is seven point six six Newtons."
            },
            {
              "id": "s6",
              "text_en": "And by Pythagoras, the square root of six point four three squared plus seven point six six squared equals ten. The vector is preserved — nothing is lost."
            }
          ]
        }
      },
