        "teacher_script": {
          "tts_sentences": [
            {
              "id": "s1",
              "text_en": "Now the clever move. Rotate our axes so one matches the incline and the other is perpendicular to it."
            },
            {
              "id": "s2",
              "text_en": "Watch the green dashed arrows appear. Suddenly m g splits into two brand new pieces."
            },
            {
              "id": "s3",
              "text_en": "The first piece is along the slope. Its magnitude is m g times sine theta — which equals nine point eight zero Newtons. That is the force pulling the block down the ramp. That is exactly what makes it slide."
            },
            {
              "id": "s4",
              "text_en": "The second piece is perpendicular to the incline. Its magnitude is m g times cosine theta — sixteen point nine seven Newtons. That is the force pushing the block into the surface."
            },
            {
              "id": "s5",
              "text_en": "The surface pushes back with the same magnitude. That pushback is called the normal reaction, N. And now you know where the famous formula N equals m g cosine theta comes from — it is just the perpendicular component of gravity."
            },
            {
              "id": "s6",
              "text_en": "The lesson is permanent. Pick axes that match the motion. Resolve the forces along them. Physics becomes simple."
            }
          ]
        }
